  "why": "TESTRNN preserves semantics and naturalness at each mutation step—using domain-specific EDA operations for text, SMILES enumeration for molecules, and small Gaussian noise for images—but does not enforce a global similarity bound to the original seed across multiple rounds of mutation. While each new mutant tracks its original seed (orig mapping) for oracle labeling, the generator does not prevent cumulative drift: mutations are applied to selected mutants rather than always relative-to the original seed, and no global L2-norm constraint is enforced during fuzzing iterations. This design corresponds to the “Medium” level, which controls perturbations relative to the previous input but does not account for cumulative distortion relative to the original seed.",
  "evidence": "• Algorithm 1 (Section VI, p.1197): orig[x'] ← orig[x], but no use of ||orig[x]–x'|| to constrain further mutations—orig is only used for the oracle check, not to bound mutations.\n• Section VI.B.1 (p.1196): “Gaussian noises with fixed mean and variance are added to the input” (per‐step naturalness), with no mention of accumulating bounds.\n• Section VII.A.3 (p.1200): Text mutations “ensure the mutated text paragraphs are always valid… meanings are reserved in all mutations,” enforcing per‐mutation semantic consistency but not a global seed‐relative bound."
